neighborhoodDescription:
Adjacent to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and directly west of Midtown, Downtown Champaign is the busy heart of this energetic college town. It is home to the Virginia Theatre, the Orpheum Children's Museum, and the Art Theater. With terrific shops, restaurants, and a vibrant nightlife, Downtown Champaign always has something happening. Local hotspots include the Black Dog Smoke & Ale House and the Blind Pig Brewery.
                        During the summer (May to October), residents head to the Land Connection Champaign Farmers' Market. College football fans head to Zuppke Field at Memorial Stadium to cheer on the Fighting Illini. Year-round events provide even more to do and include the Street Fest, the Pygmalion Music Festival, Taste of Champaign-Urbana, and the Boneyard Arts Festival.
                
                
                    Learn More About Downtown Champaign

description:
About 1009 S 2nd St
                        1009 S. Second St. Apartments, are ideal for upperclassmen with the option of either 2 bedroom, 1 Bathroom or 4 bedroom, 2 bathroom modern apartments in a great campus location that is a quick walk to classes, the ARC, and campus sporting facilities! Enjoy this modern apartments on a great campus location.  Close to the ARC, and campus sporting facilities! Our units are equipped with updated stainless steel appliances, including washer/dryer, fridge, dishwasher and oven/stove! The living room is furnished with a black leather couch and love seat, an end table and a lamp, a TV and has a sliding door leading to a private balcony. Each bedroom is furnished with a full size bed, and a desk. The apartment is fully furnished. Plenty of space for you.  Enjoy the convenience of a washer and dryer in the unit. The rents varies from $550 to $630/a month per person, for either a 4 bedroom or a 2 bedroom. There is a utility package per person ($80 for the 4 bedroom and $90 for the 2 bedroom)which includes: electric, gas, water, garbage, sewer, and high-speed internet. All services are ready when you move in! There is also ample off street parking available. We also offer individual leases! Due at the signing of the lease is first installment of rent, a security deposit ($300) and a $25 application fee. Official  move in date is August 20, but you may move in as early as August 1st for an additional payment.  Ask us about academic year leases which are also available as an option. This option is a choice for many of our students. Another aspect of this is for out of state and out of country students who may want to store their belongings over the summer or have a need for summer housing. For the cost of one monthly installment, they can immediately move in from the dorms etc. and avoid paying storage costs or short term housing and move directly into the unit they will occupy in the fall. Call or inquire at [email address removed] to schedule a touring or for some additional information.  We also encourage you to check into our website neilfotzler(dot)com for some additional information for 1 bedroom, 3 bedroom apartments as well.  My name is Virginia Rosas.  I will be glad to schedule a viewing for you!

neighborhoodDescription:
There's much more to Champaign's sister city of Urbana than you might think. It is a lively college town, home to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, it has a long and fascinating history, and it is family-friendly and beautiful. While it is usually tied to its next-door twin, Urbana stands out on its own -- Downtown Urbana is the city hub, home to Market at the Square, a farmers market that began in 1979. The historic downtown features historic architecture, bike lanes (and plenty of bike racks), sidewalk cafes, period lighting, and a wide variety of shops and restaurants.
                        In addition to the university, Urbana is home to the Beckman Institute for Advanced Science and Technology, a research institute located on the university's campus. The neighborhood attracts those with children, thanks to its top-ranking schools, and it features beautiful parks, such as Crystal Lake Park and Meadowbrook Park.
                
                
                    Learn More About Urbana

neighborhoodDescription:
Located at the intersection of Interstates 57, 72, and 74 in east central Illinois, Champaign deftly skirts the line between small town and college town. The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.
                
                
                    Learn More About Champaign

neighborhoodDescription:
Just six minutes south of the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign campus, Savoy is a suburb that offers great access to the college town. But Savoy has its own perks to attract renters seeking apartments. The suburb is slowly growing and working to improve the town year by year. There are currently plans in motion to add more parks and improve traffic infrastructure. Savoy has a low cost of living and the housing is affordable. The schools are good as well, luring in families looking to raise children in a small town. neighborhoodDescription:
Adjacent to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and directly west of Midtown, Downtown Champaign is the busy heart of this energetic college town. It is home to the Virginia Theatre, the Orpheum Children's Museum, and the Art Theater. With terrific shops, restaurants, and a vibrant nightlife, Downtown Champaign always has something happening. Local hotspots include the Black Dog Smoke & Ale House and the Blind Pig Brewery.
                        During the summer (May to October), residents head to the Land Connection Champaign Farmers' Market. College football fans head to Zuppke Field at Memorial Stadium to cheer on the Fighting Illini. Year-round events provide even more to do and include the Street Fest, the Pygmalion Music Festival, Taste of Champaign-Urbana, and the Boneyard Arts Festival.
                
                
                    Learn More About Downtown Champaign

The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.
                
                
                    Learn More About Champaign

neighborhoodDescription:
Adjacent to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and directly west of Midtown, Downtown Champaign is the busy heart of this energetic college town. It is home to the Virginia Theatre, the Orpheum Children's Museum, and the Art Theater. With terrific shops, restaurants, and a vibrant nightlife, Downtown Champaign always has something happening. Local hotspots include the Black Dog Smoke & Ale House and the Blind Pig Brewery.
                        During the summer (May to October), residents head to the Land Connection Champaign Farmers' Market. College football fans head to Zuppke Field at Memorial Stadium to cheer on the Fighting Illini. Year-round events provide even more to do and include the Street Fest, the Pygmalion Music Festival, Taste of Champaign-Urbana, and the Boneyard Arts Festival.
                
                
                    Learn More About Downtown Champaign

neighborhoodDescription:
There's much more to Champaign's sister city of Urbana than you might think. It is a lively college town, home to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, it has a long and fascinating history, and it is family-friendly and beautiful. While it is usually tied to its next-door twin, Urbana stands out on its own -- Downtown Urbana is the city hub, home to Market at the Square, a farmers market that began in 1979. The historic downtown features historic architecture, bike lanes (and plenty of bike racks), sidewalk cafes, period lighting, and a wide variety of shops and restaurants.
                        In addition to the university, Urbana is home to the Beckman Institute for Advanced Science and Technology, a research institute located on the university's campus. The neighborhood attracts those with children, thanks to its top-ranking schools, and it features beautiful parks, such as Crystal Lake Park and Meadowbrook Park.
                
                
                    Learn More About Urbana

description:
About Latitude
                        Luxury, lively, updated, convenient, pet-friendly —Latitude is your off-campus home in Champaign-Urbana, Illinois. You will LOVE WHERE YOU LIVE when you are located off University Avenue, less than a mile from Downtown and steps from UIUC. You can live in the middle of where everything happens while enjoying the comfort and convenience of our community. We're located within minutes of Savoy and Staley, with easy access to I-74 making Latitude the perfect location to commute or work from home. Our apartments are a short walk to County Market and a quick ride to Walgreens and Target on Greene Street. We're located on the MTD Bus Route with a bus stop on the property to make your travels easier. Live in the middle of where everything happens, while enjoying the comfort and convenience of our community. 

You don’t have to step outside your home to experience quintessential Champaign-Urbana living. At Latitude, you will enjoy an active lifestyle. We offer a 24-hour Fitness Center, co-working lounges with free printing, and individual study rooms, all with high-speed Wi-Fi. Join UAVE Crossfit gym for an onsite workout or take a break with Bearology beverage bar. If you want a quiet space to relax or work, enjoy our rooftop terrace with hammocks, fire pits, and outdoor seating. Swim in our resort-style pool with a surrounding sun deck or take in the views from our poolside treehouse lounge. Experience the diverse restaurants on University Avenue, Main Street, and Green Street. If you want fresh air, Busey Woods and Crystal Lake Parks are only 1.5 miles away. Say 'Goodbye' to standard apartment living, and 'Hello' to the high-end conveniences our amazing location offers. 

We believe in a live-learn community that cultivates creativity, inspires ingenuity, and empowers you to make choices that indulge your spirit of adventure. We offer outstanding customer service that puts you first. With modern furniture packages available, high-end finishes and most utilities included, our residents enjoy our inclusive community. With 1, 2 & 4 bedroom apartment homes near Downtown Champaign, we’re perfect for the modern professional or student alike. We welcome students from University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, Parkland College, or any surrounding schools. We want you to experience a new level of living with Latitude. When you live at Latitude, you choose an experience that will allow you to embrace your highest potential throughout and beyond your college years. Live fully, boldly, and inspired as you connect with a community that celebrates you for being you! Text “LIVELATITUDE” to 51378.

The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.
                
                
                    Learn More About Champaign

neighborhoodDescription:
Adjacent to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and directly west of Midtown, Downtown Champaign is the busy heart of this energetic college town. It is home to the Virginia Theatre, the Orpheum Children's Museum, and the Art Theater. With terrific shops, restaurants, and a vibrant nightlife, Downtown Champaign always has something happening. Local hotspots include the Black Dog Smoke & Ale House and the Blind Pig Brewery.
                        During the summer (May to October), residents head to the Land Connection Champaign Farmers' Market. College football fans head to Zuppke Field at Memorial Stadium to cheer on the Fighting Illini. Year-round events provide even more to do and include the Street Fest, the Pygmalion Music Festival, Taste of Champaign-Urbana, and the Boneyard Arts Festival.
                
                
                    Learn More About Downtown Champaign

description:
About 506 E. White Champaign
                        Large furnished 2 bedroom apartments (900-1,050 sq. ft.) include: kitchen, dining room, spacious living room with a ‘pass though’ bar to the kitchen, bedrooms, and a screened-in balcony. The bathroom has a full-size tub/shower and a separate area with two sinks, so a person does not tie up the entire bathroom. Units on the top floor have cathedral ceilings. 

Included in all units: free super-fast fiber optics Internet, refrigerator, stove, microwave, garbage disposal and dishwasher. The building has a bicycle rack and key-access to a large on-site laundry facility. Assigned off-street sheltered parking is also available. 

These apartments are located: 1 block west of the engineering quad; 2 blocks from County Market grocery store; and across the street from Far East grocery store. A one-minute walk gets you to the bus stop with four frequent bus lines (every 10 minutes for Yellow and Teal) to zoom you to anywhere on or off campus.

                506 E. White Champaign is an apartment community located in Champaign County and the 61820 ZIP Code. This area is served by the Champaign Community Unit School District 4 attendance zone.

neighborhoodDescription:
There's much more to Champaign's sister city of Urbana than you might think. It is a lively college town, home to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, it has a long and fascinating history, and it is family-friendly and beautiful. While it is usually tied to its next-door twin, Urbana stands out on its own -- Downtown Urbana is the city hub, home to Market at the Square, a farmers market that began in 1979. The historic downtown features historic architecture, bike lanes (and plenty of bike racks), sidewalk cafes, period lighting, and a wide variety of shops and restaurants.
                        In addition to the university, Urbana is home to the Beckman Institute for Advanced Science and Technology, a research institute located on the university's campus. The neighborhood attracts those with children, thanks to its top-ranking schools, and it features beautiful parks, such as Crystal Lake Park and Meadowbrook Park.
                
                
                    Learn More About Urbana

neighborhoodDescription:
Just six minutes south of the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign campus, Savoy is a suburb that offers great access to the college town. But Savoy has its own perks to attract renters seeking apartments. The suburb is slowly growing and working to improve the town year by year. There are currently plans in motion to add more parks and improve traffic infrastructure. Savoy has a low cost of living and the housing is affordable. The schools are good as well, luring in families looking to raise children in a small town. Conveniently, Savoy has a direct connection to several metropolitan areas through three local Interstate highways. The town has Willard Airport on the southern edge of town for locals who like to travel.
                        Savoy has all the entertainment of a classic American small town. Indulge in nostalgia at Old Orchard Lanes and Links, an old-school style bowling alley with mini golf, or Skateland roller rink. Catch a 3D movie at GQT Savoy 16 or sing you heart out at Star Karaoke.

neighborhoodDescription:
Adjacent to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and directly west of Midtown, Downtown Champaign is the busy heart of this energetic college town. It is home to the Virginia Theatre, the Orpheum Children's Museum, and the Art Theater. With terrific shops, restaurants, and a vibrant nightlife, Downtown Champaign always has something happening. Local hotspots include the Black Dog Smoke & Ale House and the Blind Pig Brewery.
                        During the summer (May to October), residents head to the Land Connection Champaign Farmers' Market. College football fans head to Zuppke Field at Memorial Stadium to cheer on the Fighting Illini. Year-round events provide even more to do and include the Street Fest, the Pygmalion Music Festival, Taste of Champaign-Urbana, and the Boneyard Arts Festival.
                
                
                    Learn More About Downtown Champaign

The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.
                
                
                    Learn More About Champaign

neighborhoodDescription:
There's much more to Champaign's sister city of Urbana than you might think. It is a lively college town, home to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, it has a long and fascinating history, and it is family-friendly and beautiful. While it is usually tied to its next-door twin, Urbana stands out on its own -- Downtown Urbana is the city hub, home to Market at the Square, a farmers market that began in 1979. The historic downtown features historic architecture, bike lanes (and plenty of bike racks), sidewalk cafes, period lighting, and a wide variety of shops and restaurants.
                        In addition to the university, Urbana is home to the Beckman Institute for Advanced Science and Technology, a research institute located on the university's campus. The neighborhood attracts those with children, thanks to its top-ranking schools, and it features beautiful parks, such as Crystal Lake Park and Meadowbrook Park.

description:
About 503 E Clark St Champaign, IL 61820
                        August 2023 / On-Campus Large Studio Apartments

These large fully-furnished studio apartments are 400 sq. ft. and include a large living room/bedroom, a kitchen area, a bathroom with a full-size tub/shower, and 36 sq. ft. of closet space. Rent includes high-speed fiber optics Internet, water and all commons fees, but does not include an individually metered electricity bill. Assigned off-street parking is also available. The rent is $684 per month for first floor apartments and $704 per month for second and third floor apartments.

The apartment is located less than two blocks from the University of Illinois engineering quad, closest to ECE and Beckman. A ten-minute walk gets you to the Illini Union. A one-minute walk gets you to the bus stop with four frequent bus lines (every 10 minutes for Yellow and Teal) to zoom you to anywhere on or off campus. It is a 5-minute walk to the County Market grocery and across the street from the Far East grocery. The building has a security entrance, a bicycle rack, and a new on-site laundry facility/mailroom. Also new in each apartment: refrigerators, stoves, hot water heaters, kitchen sinks, faucets and countertops. The commons areas were newly carpeted and painted in 2022. New windows will be installed in each apartment before August 2023.

This property is designated by the public health district as a NO SMOKING building: no smoking is allowed anywhere inside the building or outside within 15 ft. of the perimeter.

NOTE: These apartments may be shown virtually or in-person.

neighborhoodDescription:
Located at the intersection of Interstates 57, 72, and 74 in east central Illinois, Champaign deftly skirts the line between small town and college town. The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.

neighborhoodDescription:
Located at the intersection of Interstates 57, 72, and 74 in east central Illinois, Champaign deftly skirts the line between small town and college town. The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.

neighborhoodDescription:
Located just east of Sacramento and adjacent to the breathtaking scenery of Folsom Lake, you’ll find Folsom, California. This suburb offers its residents the essence of California living, with tree-lined boulevards, lovely stucco homes, and year-round warm breezes. Located on a charming landscape, Folsom features the very best of amenities, comfort, and luxury. Renting an apartment in Folsom allows its residents to get the best of quiet neighborhoods and picturesque architecture, with a tranquil ambiance that you’re sure to love in your next apartment.
                        Take a family trip to the Folsom City Zoo Sanctuary or visit one of Folsom’s historic walking areas, Sutter Street. Grab a show or see your favorite artists in concert at the Harris Center or engage with Folsom’s history at the Folsom Powerhouse and the Folsom Historical Museum. Hang your hat in Folsom, California and get the best of both worlds every day.
                
                
                    Learn More About Folsom

Located at the intersection of Interstates 57, 72, and 74 in east central Illinois, Champaign deftly skirts the line between small town and college town. The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.

Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. neighborhoodDescription:
Located at the intersection of Interstates 57, 72, and 74 in east central Illinois, Champaign deftly skirts the line between small town and college town. The University of Illinois largely defines the city, with nearly 45,000 students enrolled (the city’s population totals around 85,000); as a result, Champaign is home to a growing sector of tech startups and other entrepreneurial endeavors growing out of the university’s research community and recent graduates.
                        The rental market includes a number of highly affordable options, including many apartments under $600 per month. Expect your schedule to be packed with community events when you live in Champaign, from the popular and wide-ranging Boneyard arts festival to the Sweetcorn Festival in neighboring Urbana. As the hometown of late movie critic Roger Ebert, Champaign’s historic Virginia Theatre hosts an annual film festival in his honor.
                
                
                    Learn More About Champaign
